<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,566,1018]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,338,643,669]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Discussion:</emphasis>
A revision of the 
<typeStatus box="[551,654,644,670]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[694,857,644,669]" class="Arachnida" family="Hydryphantidae" genus="Hydryphantes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vastipalpis">
<emphasis box="[694,857,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. vastipalpis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows that the posterior right legs are misshapen (III-L- 
<number box="[231,246,682,708]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="4.0">4</number>
very thickened, III-L- 
<number box="[523,537,682,708]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="6.0">6</number>
reduced, distally narrowed and with distorted claws, IV-L- 
<number box="[1274,1306,682,708]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1-3</number>
extremely inflated, IV-L- 
<number box="[331,368,721,747]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4-6</number>
reduced stepwise in dimensions). Along with the fact that since the first description no further specimens with similarly enlarged palps have been found, these observations suggest that the general morphology of the specimen is caused by developmental disturbance. The synonymization proposal of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundblad" box="[151,348,837,863]" pageId="14" pageNumber="32" refString="Lundblad, C. O. (1962) Die Hydracarinen Schwedens. II. Arkiv for Zoologi 14 (2), 1 - 635." type="journal article" year="1962">
Lundblad (
<number box="[279,340,837,863]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1962.0">1962</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
should be accepted: The specimen is a misshapen individual of 
<taxonomicName box="[1101,1246,837,862]" class="Arachnida" family="Hydryphantidae" genus="Hydryphantes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexuosus">
<emphasis box="[1101,1246,837,862]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. flexuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,566,1018]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Interestingly, among specimens from the collecting site near Murcia, one female has the frontal shield nearly completely reduced, while from all other points of view it agrees with the other specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Hydryphantidae" genus="Hydryphantes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexuosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. flexuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the area of the collecting site, most inland waters are highly saline, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1159,1305,953,978]" class="Arachnida" family="Hydryphantidae" genus="Hydryphantes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexuosus">
<emphasis box="[1159,1305,953,978]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">H. flexuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here the only, but very frequently found, species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
